Since I was young, the parents  in my city would tell the kids to ALWAYS be quiet and not be too laugh because if we do, an ‚Äúevil creature‚Äù will come to our town and disturb us. We all listened to them, because as a kid, you don‚Äôt really know anything, so you have to believe. We would never talk loud, laugh loud, and we would always walk around the house with cloths under our feet to stay quiet. Then one day, my friend Gino came over my place. He was not feeling well that day. He was having stomach pain. Then suddenly, Gino said to me ‚Äúwanna know a secret?‚Äù And I said ‚ÄúSure‚Äù then he let out a loud fart. We laughed. text: This is my theory. The world which this takes place in is a few years in the future after a major civilization has broken apart. A small community of people forms together to create a self-sustaining town. Some creatures from the nearby radioactive wasteland hunt to town by old the sounds they make. The girl in the trailer is adopted and regularly visits the grave of her mother on the bridge. The mother is pregnant as she is seen holding her stomach in several shots and giving birth in the last, this will be the inciting incident rather than the lamp falling. The father and son regularly go on this trail of sand to hunt for the families food, as well as the local cornfield where the monsters reside.

text: Wow, it looks like¬†Hollywood came up with a refreshingly original concept for once. I hope the movie holds up to the trailer. I almost get a creepypasta vibe from this. text: I'm so curious about the plot of this movie. 1) how in the world did they get there? Like did they live there before the threat of monsters?? Because moving furniture into a house that you can't make a peep in is just impossible. Also why would anyone wanna purposely live there if they have to be utterly silent? That tells me they had to live there prior to whatever monster there is, or they are in a post apocalyptic world where they found shelter in the country.  2) As others pointed out... how in the world can whatever they're hiding from not see the house or other infrastructure on the property but hear the tiniest whisper? Furthermore how would whatever it is be able to hunt without seeing?  3) I'm assuming they are no where near a beach... so where In the world did he get all that sand from?  4) if you are hiding, why are they outside in the open? The little kid crossed the bridge and the woman was doing laundry which suggests they've established some kinda life there. But still why are you outside??  All in all I'm very curious about this plot. So many unanswered questions.

text: I remember when I was a teen, I had a nightmare about gigantic, monstruous jaws living underground. When someone or something was making noise on the surface, the jaws appeared and devoured it exactly where the sound occured. The whole world became silent, and there were holes everywhere. There was almost nothing left, no animals, no humans, no trees because of the wind making the leaves move. I remember being completely paralyzed, even breathing was scary.  It's really weird to see a decade later a horror movie with the same concept as one of my worst nightmare ever.

text: After Jim and Pam leave Dunder Mifflin, the company crashes and burns. Angela leaves Dwight in search of a more fitting life. Dwight consoles in Jim for help, so he flies back to Scranton with the kids to give Pam a few days to herself. Jim calls Angela to figure out what's going on and they decide to meet up at the farm, but Dwight is nowhere to be found. Later on that afternoon, Cece wakes up in the middle of the field after falling asleep in her room. Jim figured Mose was being his normal weird self, so he asks Angela where he's staying so he can talk to Mose. But Mose died 2 years ago. Now, faced with an upset Dwight and the haunting suspicion that he is out to get both Jim and Angela, they are forced to fight to save the lives of the kids and themselves.

text: Great acting...in a really really stupid movie with a not-scary monster. Eyes, even ones that barely work, would have made the thing more scary. And I hate silly errors such as the monster making easy work of a grain silo but not ripping through the roof of a rusty old truck.  And really...everyone knew the thing had super hearing, yet no one figured out that some feedback would drive it nuts? Huh...sounds drive aliens nuts...where have I heard that before?  Oh yeah! Indian Love Song killed the silly aliens in Mars Attacks. Did we need to dig up  Slim Whitman to tell the world the plot of that movie and save the real world?  And really....the things can't see anything,  but one slapped a running  raccoon down like it was the side of a barn?  Sorry, but a great idea got ruined by Hollywood yet again. My wife was mildly scared, but she is scared of daddy long legs spiders and people with nose piercings. Skip this one until it's free on Netflix.

While I personally don‚Äôt find it scary (it‚Äôs hard to scare me and that‚Äôs not why I like horror in the first place), this film has a unique and wonderful flair to it!! It‚Äôs more like a thriller. But if you want to feel tense and watch a great film! Go see it. I was surprised at just HOW much storytelling you can do by only using body language. text: I hate to fucking do this but i have to give an angry rant out on the movie and i fucking hate to do that to a movie that i like and could have been so fucking good  HUGE SPOILERS AHEAD  You know what i hate the most, when i finish a movie and i really liked it but something bothers me, then i sit down and think about the movie for a while, i do that after any movie i really liked and is worth thinking about after. So in this movie what bothered me is the simple premise that the more you think about has no goddamn sense, the monsters react to the tinyests of sounds, ok, then how the fuck are they not gathered around the watterfall? They grew tired of it? How did that racoon survive that long, or the birds shown at start they have to land sometimes, or the fucking fishes, i mean they attack anything that makes a sound even the tv, so how are they not out there hitting the fucking trees cause the wind is making sound through the leafs, or the house i mean its a fucking wooden house those things make sounds on their own, or the familly when its asleep, what they dont talk in their sleep or fucking snore?and the metod they found out to beat them is idk, like the millitary wouldnt find out earlier, it was even in the fucking news that they react to sound. This movies own rules violate themselves and the more you think about it the less sense they make. I hate when movies with good base stories and so much huge potential do that, couldnt they just make so the monsters react to only living things or only human vocal cords? and there pooofff i fixed the plot holes now just center the story around that, jesus christ is this movie not believable, and i actually hate that cause this movie had great acting pace and a good premise, it could have been so fucking good. Am not gonna say its bad its defo worth a watch in regards to all the shit today that comes out and is entertaining and suspense but god does the logic bother me. Another type of identicall movie is "signs" with mel gibson now that movie did it right, this movie is worth a watch but im actually so angry cause it could have been almost as good if the writers had just a little more higher  IQ

text: ( spoilers)This movie was easy money. There was little to no dialogue, which makes sense, but when there WAS dialogue, it was cheesy and cliche. They kept using the same set pieces, so production cost on that was probably saved. The characters had no personality at all, so you even if they died(hypothetically) you wouldn‚Äôt be saddened.  The story had so many unanswered questions ( Where‚Äôd the monsters come from, why they‚Äôre here, what are they, etc.) and the ‚Äúsuspense‚Äù was just predictable scenes of artificial tension; ending with a loud noise.   There were things that made sense (the sand on the pathway, painting the wood to know where to step), and things that did not( why are they staying at the creaky wooden house instead of near the waterfall, why do they have hanged paintings that can fall and make noise, why didn‚Äôt they think of the solution of high-pithed frequency to fight something that relies entirely on sound earlier, WHY WOULD THEY HAVE A BABY THAT WILL CRY LOUDLY THE MOMENT IT‚ÄôS BORN).  Overall, i thought the concept was interesting, but execution was dreadful. There wasn‚Äôt any true suspense that didn‚Äôt feel so forced, no built relationship with the characters, and the ‚Äúlore‚Äù of the movie was essentially non-existent as far as I could tell.  2/10 Only my opinion

text: ‚Äî‚ÄîSPOILER WARNING‚Äî‚Äî For those of you who are wondering why the heck the family would chose to have a baby in a time where the faintest of sounds would kill them, the movie gives hints as to why. It could very well be that the couple are very devout Christians. The film gives us several hints: One: They pray before their meals. Two: they erected a cross for their deceased child and three: the pregnancy itself. If they were devout Christians, they would most likely be against abortion and be pro-life. It could also be that the wife wanted another son after their youngest had died. Either way, they prepared for this by making a soundproof basement, a soundproof cradle complete with an oxygen mask, and an elaborate diversion to detract from her screams during childbirth. There were other religious themes woven into it as well such as self sacrifice and the value of love and family roles. Sooooo... it‚Äôs not to far-fetched when you put it all together. TLDR: Family is Christian and pro-life

text: Went to see this movie, lets just say I bought a ticket for a whole seat but I only used the edge of it.  But really, as a filmstudent we get lessons about how important soundscape, noise and music is to a movie and to create tension of feelings. This movie is like the perfect antiserum for that thinking. I don't even think I heard one note playing yet it was the most intense horror film of the decade dare I say. It does so much right, by breaking the rules. My teacher asked me how I liked this movie saying something along the lines of "I can't imagine how this movie could create tension" I responded with, *deep breath* "BOI".

text: What a pointless piece of crap. I don't see how the people lived as long as they did given how inept they were. ***************** Spoilers Ahead ****************************   The father didn't bother to take his shotgun wherever he went. Not even an ax. It's especially bad that he didn't take it when he went looking for the kids at the end. But then I guess they would not have a reason to show his self sacrifice at the end. Also pointless. He didn't even try to take a swing at the thing with the ax. And the greatest minds on the planet couldn't figure out that a creature with super sensitive hearing might be incapacitated by high frequency sound at high volume? The girl and wife just happened to stumble on that at the last minute. Yeah right. Pretty much as crappy an ending as "Signs" where the guy discovers the aliens can be killed with water. I mean, they invade a planet 75% covered with water (it even falls from the sky) and don't even bother to wear a raincoat? Hell, in this situation people could have set traps using sound to lure the creatures. Simple. Clearly they aren't "indestructible" since she took one down with one shotgun blast. Dear old dad could have done the same had he remembered to bring the gun. Just a stupid plot.

text: NO SPOILERS, JUST A GENERAL THOUGHT.   I just saw the film. My God, I couldn't fault it. You see, the plot/concept of the film is quite fascinating, it has a massive potential to become an intense thriller, yet it would be hard to pull off. I've seen bad films with a great plots.   They did more than pull it off. It was so good that it pulled my weave off. The ambience/atmosphere was intense. The build-up of the scenes, camera angles and movements, cinematography and scriptwriting was magnificent! This is stellar quality! My sense of hearing augmented and was compelled. This is how you make a thriller. It thrills all of your senses, makes your heartbeat skip swiftly, drives you to the edge of your seat and could also make you cry and break your heart.   If you haven't seen this, drop everything and watch it! Close the lights, put some earphones on and watch it alone for better and more scintillating experience. That's what I did. And brace yourselves (your heart, most especially) for a one hell of a ride!   P.S *I'll throw a fit if this film doesn't get nominated for an Oscar cough cough John Krasinski for Best Director and Emily Blunt for Best Actress in a Lead Role*

text: Very interesting premise! i always love end of the world survival movies. What would one do, if noise would be the death of you? How would you adept? What obstacles would you run into. Its like they created a universe of their own. I don't often like movies without a clear story, but seeing how they survive against these aliens is really interesting. Though it was a little odd seeing husband and wife in the movie xD  They didn't need to 'act' as partners, cause they are. And you could tell.  They put a lot of emotion in their acting. No wonder Emily Blunt hesitated for a moment wether she would want to enter such a dark story. But darn they're good at their jobs. Regardless of the good acting, the movie wasn't scary to me at all. I'm mentioning this because it was categorized as horror.   Props to John Krasinski for directing this! It was solid.

text: This isn't a horror movie at all...   I mean, the movie itself is a solid 6 (I guess?) but I couldn't help but not like it. I feel like some situations could've been elaborated a lot better. The movie wanted to pass a message with every scene - which it does very well (the traumatic experience that hurt a family bond, the parents that tried their best but were overwhelmed by an adverse situation, the kid that didn't understand what was going on and thought she was to blame, plus the awareness of being impaired and probably feeling like a burden, and so on and so forth), and every character is very distinct. But I feel like they tried to address a lot of things at the same time and kinda forgot about the plot (which has abysmal holes to it and ended up a little cliche), and the ending could've been a lot better.   All things considered, I'd say watch it and take your own conclusions, although don't expect a horror movie. It's 60% drama, 25% thriller and maybe 15% horror.

text: It really is rare to see an instant/soon-to-be-immortalized-as-history-progresses/ classic unfolding before your very eyes. I am so glad that I got a ticket to see this film on one of the many Saturday nights in the summer of '18, just so I can claim that I first saw it in theatres. I hear people who were lucky enough to watch Elm Street, Friday the 13th, and The Shining when they were in their initial theatrical runs brag about their experience, and they all held onto their stubs. I have the stub from this one locked away in a stash box, because I'm sure it'll be worth money in the future.
